g_elicits_reasoning_chunk_003.pdf: source (examples in this dataset already included reasoning steps like a chain of thought). 2 Fig- ure 6 shows that these prompts performed comparably with our manually written exemplars, also substantially outperforming standard prompting.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_004.pdf: Acknowledgements We thank Jacob Devlin, Claire Cui, Andrew Dai, and Ellie Pavlick for providing feedback on the paper. We thank Jacob Austin, Yuhuai Wu, Henryk Michalewski, Aitor Lewkowycz, Charles Sutton, and Aakanksha Chowdhery for helpful discussions.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_005.pdf: Qiu Ran, Yankai Lin, Peng Li, Jie Zhou, and Zhiyuan Liu. 2019.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_006.pdf: A Frequently Asked Questions A.1 Why does increasing model scale improve chain-of-thought prompting? The ﬁnding that successful chain-of-thought reasoning predictably emerges only at certain model scales is intriguing.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_007.pdf: multi-step reasoning, (2) a large language model is used, and (3) the scaling curve is relatively ﬂat. Conversely, the beneﬁts are smaller when one or more of these conditions are not met.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_008.pdf: Table 4: Standard prompting versus chain of thought prompting on ﬁve commonsense reasoning benchmarks. Chain of thought prompting is an emergent ability of model scale—it does not positively impact performance until used with a model of sufﬁcient scale.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_009.pdf: Perhaps the most-related work here is Recchia (2021), which shows that ﬁnetuning enables longhand module operations, which has previously been difﬁcult for performers. Whereas work in this direction is often task-speciﬁc and uses ﬁnetuning, we show that chain-of-thought prompting works for a broad range of tasks without any ﬁnetuning.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_010.pdf: We found that the remaining chains of thought (27 of 50; 54%) would require substantial edits to make into a correct chain of thought. Almost all cases here involved some error in semantic understanding (see Table 11: “semantic understanding error”), and 8 of the 27 also had incoherent chain of thoughts, meaning that some statements in the generated chain of thought did not follow from prior ones or violated basic world knowledge (see Table 11: “incoherent chain of thought error”).\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_011.pdf: • StrategyQA (Geva et al., 2021): we use the open-domain setting (question-only set) from BIG-bench collaboration (2021): https://github.com/google/BIG-bench/ tree/main/bigbench/benchmark_tasks/strategyqa. The original dataset is from https://github.com/eladsegal/strategyqa, MIT license: https://github.com/ eladsegal/strategyqa/blob/main/LICENSE.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_012.pdf: Table 19: Examples of correct and incorrect chains of thought produced by PaLM 540B on SayCan robot planning tasks. QUESTION : I spilled my coke on the table, could you throw it away and then bring me something to help clean?\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_013.pdf: Table 23: Few-shot exemplars for full chain of thought prompt for the coinﬂip task. PROMPT FOR COIN FLIP Q: Q: A coin is heads up.\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_014.pdf: Table 27: Few-shot exemplars for full chain of thought prompt for Sports Understanding. PROMPT FOR SPORTS UNDERSTANDING Q: Is the following sentence plausible?\n- 2201.11903_cot_prompting_elicits_reasoning_chunk_015.pdf: Table 30: Few-shot exemplars for full chain of thought prompt for math word problems. These exemplars are the same as in Table 20, except that the chains of thought were written by a different annotator (“Annotator C” instead of “Annotator A”).\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
